commit.message: Easy way to obtain data from response headers

Added restclient-http-send-current-suppress-response-buffer command

This command will send current request as usual but it will not display response buffer.

Update README.md

fix typos in readme
Display request in fundamental mode if it's too big

fix: lexical-let is void when using cl-lib

cl-lib does not provide lexical-let, making the use
of `run-hook` impossible when Emacs Version is higher than 26.

Enabling lexical binding and replacing `lexical-let` occurrences
with `let` solves the issue for Emacs 25 through 29.

Make sure restclient is loaded first

As restclient-jq isn't useful without restclient, we might as well
make sure that restclient is loaded. This simplifies registering the
result-func and avoids warnings from byte-compile and package-lint.

Add standard keywords and version

Fixes some package-lint warnings.

Add docstrings to all defuns.

Fixes checkdoc warnings.

Mark second argument to restclient-jq-json-var-function as unused

Fixes a byte-compile warning.
improve the require form for cl-lib

'cl is deprecated in emacs 27 and beyond

the previously common practice of rquiring 'cl now throws a
deprecation warning. Update the package requirements to cl-lib.
enable file-level lexical binding
Allow the omission of response header summary via customizable variable

Trim URL whitespace so that requests still work correctly

When a URL had any trailing whitespace, the request would needlessly fail.

Explicitly require subr-x and cl packages

The subr-x is required for when-let and cl is required for lexical-let.
Use cl-lib as cl was deprecated

Update README with example of hook on POST

The only existing examples are for GET and don't have a body.
fix two remaining "resetclient" typos
Making package-lint happy: dependencies and function names.
Fixed typo. Added proper dependency for "lexical-let".
Add back jq IP example

Add more useful Elisp example to readme

Thanks for making this and adding the useful request hook functionality recently.

I wanted to set variables from JSON responses, but can't install jq on my work computer. After playing around  a bit, I found that using the built-in `json-read` is works nicely and is still quite readable for simple parsing.

This PR updates the README to add an example of parsing using Elisp so other users can see how the new request-hooks can still be useful without installing jq or jq-mode.

fixes #236: README.md: update POST example "HSP" => "HCPUB"

The "HSP" project is no longer available at the upstream jira.atlassian.com
host, so the POST example that used that project name in the 'jql' query
stopped working. This change simply replaces "HSP" with "HCPUB", which is a
project ("HipChat") that is still available at that location, so restores the
example to working order.
fix bug in run-hook & support for reading vars in elisp expressions
Support for setting variables from responses

No longer set url-mime-accept-string et al. permanently (#215)

Setting these variables permanently (aka globally) causes them to
affect the behavior of unrelated packages that also use the `url'
library.

By using let-bindings we can limit the effect to a single request.

Re https://github.com/magit/forge/issues/153.
Introduced restclient-response-mode (#200)

Speed up JSON pretty-printing with Emacs 27 (#208)

Emacs 27 json.el uses `replace-buffer-contents' for pretty-printing which is
great because it keeps point and markers intact but can be very slow with huge
minimalized JSON.  We don't need that feature here because we're at the
beginnning or end of the JSON anyway, so disable it by binding
`json-pretty-print-max-secs' to 0.

Type and subtype in media types should be treated as case insensitive (#204)

See [RFC 2616 - Section 3.7](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#section-3.7)
Moved body collapse to spearate minor mode activated by default
